2026-04-16 12:11:16 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Control Output Cable (+) connection to switch / internal node'] hypothesis_explanation='Diagnostics show: (1) PSU module is healthy and delivering +12 V with correct polarity. (2) The load module—including its diode, main lamp, indicator lamp, and return path—has correct continuity and normal resistances. (3) Within the control module, the +12 V from the PSU reaches the switch input, the switch itself has continuity, and the − conductor passes straight through correctly. However, the Control Output Cable (+) has its port ‘p’ floating and is not tied to the switched +12 V node; only its port ‘n’ is connected downstream to the Load Input Cable (+). This means there is an internal open/misconnection between the switch output node and the Control Output Cable (+) conductor that should carry +12 V to the load. As a result, the load-input (+) node never sees +12 V even when the switch is closed, preventing any current flow through the diode and lamps. The root cause is therefore a wiring fault/open connection on the + output path inside the control module (e.g., the switched + node not soldered or mis-terminated to the Control Output Cable (+) lead). Repairing or reworking this specific connection so that the switch output node is properly connected to the Control Output Cable (+) should restore lamp operation.'
